window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["pericardial-disease"]={"slug": "pericardial-disease", "title": "Pericardial Disease", "tagline": "Acute and recurrent pericarditis, tamponade, and the constriction-versus-restriction problem, worked from bedside to echo lab to cath lab.", "level": 2, "readMin": 42, "takeaways": ["Acute pericarditis is a clinical diagnosis: 2 of 4 criteria (pleuritic chest pain, friction rub, widespread ST elevation/PR depression, new or worsening effusion). First-line therapy is an NSAID <strong>plus</strong> colchicine, which roughly halves recurrence; taper by CRP, not the calendar.", "Colchicine is the single most important drug in pericarditis. Add it to the first attack (3 months) and to recurrences (6 months). Avoid corticosteroids early unless there is a specific indication because low-dose steroids drive recurrence.", "Recurrent pericarditis that is colchicine-resistant and steroid-dependent is increasingly recognized as an IL-1 driven autoinflammatory disease. Rilonacept (RHAPSODY) and anakinra (AIRTRIP) produce rapid, durable remission and enable steroid weaning.", "Tamponade is a clinical and hemodynamic diagnosis. Echo (RA systolic collapse, RV diastolic collapse, respirophasic tricuspid/mitral inflow variation, plethoric IVC) supports it, but a decompensating patient with a rub and hypotension does not wait for a perfect study.", "Constriction versus restriction is settled by respiration: constriction shows enhanced ventricular interdependence (septal bounce, mitral inflow variation >25%, hepatic vein expiratory diastolic flow reversal, RV-LV systolic pressure discordance) and <em>annulus reversus</em>, while restriction shows the opposite with reduced e'.", "The square-root sign, equalization of end-diastolic pressures within about 5 mmHg, and a systolic area index >1.1 on simultaneous RV-LV tracings are the invasive fingerprints of constriction."], "sections": [{"id": "overview", "title": "The pericardium: anatomy, physiology, and why it matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The pericardium is a two-layered sac. The visceral pericardium (epicardium) is a monolayer of mesothelium adherent to the heart; the parietal pericardium is a tough, largely acellular collagen-and-elastin membrane. Between them sits 15 to 50 mL of plasma ultrafiltrate. The sac anchors the heart, limits acute distention, and mechanically couples the two ventricles. Disease of the pericardium expresses itself through a small number of syndromes: <strong>inflammation</strong> (acute and recurrent pericarditis), <strong>fluid</strong> (effusion and tamponade), and <strong>scar</strong> (constriction). Much of the clinical difficulty is that these overlap and that constriction mimics restrictive cardiomyopathy."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The dominant physiologic fact is that the normal pericardium is relatively <strong>non-compliant</strong> at physiologic volumes. The pericardial pressure-volume curve is flat then steeply rising, so a small, rapidly accumulating effusion (100 to 200 mL from a wall rupture) can tamponade, while a slowly accumulating chronic effusion may exceed 1 to 2 L without hemodynamic compromise because the sac remodels. This is the reason a stab wound tamponades and a chronic malignant effusion often does not."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Ventricular interdependence is the unifying concept.</strong> Because a stiff or fluid-filled pericardium fixes total cardiac volume, the two ventricles compete for a fixed space across the interventricular septum. Inspiration augments right-heart filling, which pushes the septum leftward and impairs left-heart filling, and vice versa on expiration. Every hallmark of both tamponade and constriction (pulsus paradoxus, septal bounce, respirophasic inflow variation, RV-LV systolic discordance) is a downstream expression of exaggerated interdependence. Learn the physiology once and the tables below become derivable rather than memorized."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Ventricular interdependence", "def": "Filling of one ventricle influences the other because they share the septum within a constrained pericardial space. Exaggerated in constriction and tamponade."}, {"term": "Dissociation of intrathoracic and intracardiac pressures", "def": "Hallmark of constriction: the rigid pericardium shields the heart from thoracic pressure swings, so inspiration lowers pulmonary venous (thoracic) pressure without a matching drop inside the LV, reducing the LA-to-LV gradient and left-heart filling."}, {"term": "Transmural distending pressure", "def": "Intracavitary minus pericardial pressure. Tamponade is physiologically a fall in transmural pressure toward zero, so chamber filling collapses even when intracavitary pressure looks 'normal'."}]}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Pericardial anatomy, effusion appearance, and pericardial calcification on cross-sectional imaging are worth reviewing visually.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: pericardial imaging"}]}, {"id": "acute-diagnosis", "title": "Acute pericarditis: diagnostic criteria", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Acute pericarditis is a clinical diagnosis. Per the 2015 ESC guideline, diagnosis requires at least <strong>2 of 4</strong> criteria. Two supportive findings (elevated CRP/ESR and pericardial inflammation on CT or CMR) increase confidence but are not required."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "ESC diagnostic criteria for acute pericarditis (need 2 of 4)", "head": ["Criterion", "Characteristic detail"], "rows": [["Pericarditic chest pain", "Sharp, pleuritic, positional; worse supine, relieved by sitting forward; often radiates to the trapezius ridge (phrenic nerve). Present in most cases."], ["Pericardial friction rub", "Superficial scratchy/squeaky sound, best at the left sternal border in end-expiration leaning forward; classically triphasic; highly specific, often intermittent."], ["ECG changes", "New widespread concave ST elevation and/or PR depression across most leads; reciprocal PR elevation and ST depression in aVR."], ["Pericardial effusion", "New or worsening effusion on echocardiography (often small)."]]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The ECG classically evolves through four stages: (1) diffuse concave ST elevation with PR depression, (2) normalization, (3) diffuse T-wave inversions, (4) resolution. The key discriminators from STEMI are the <strong>diffuse</strong> (non-coronary) distribution, absence of reciprocal ST depression (except aVR and V1), PR-segment depression, and absence of Q waves or ST elevation exceeding T-wave height. The Spodick sign (down-sloping TP segment) is a supportive clue."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Always exclude the dangerous mimics before you commit to pericarditis.</strong> Diffuse ST elevation can be STEMI (especially a wraparound LAD), and pleuritic chest pain with an effusion can be aortic dissection with hemopericardium or pulmonary embolism. A troponin rise means <em>myopericarditis</em> (myocardial involvement) and mandates ischemia exclusion, often with coronary imaging, plus activity restriction."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Myopericarditis", "def": "Predominantly pericarditic syndrome with troponin elevation but preserved LV function. Generally good prognosis; restrict exercise until troponin normalizes and CMR/echo reassure."}, {"term": "Perimyocarditis", "def": "Predominantly myocardial involvement with new wall-motion abnormality or reduced EF plus pericarditic features; higher-risk, closer follow-up."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic for the ECG of acute pericarditis: 'PReD ST'</strong> — <strong>PR</strong> <strong>De</strong>pression and diffuse <strong>ST</strong> elevation. In aVR everything flips (PR up, ST down). If you see concave-up ST elevation across multiple territories with PR depression, think pericardium before coronary."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Review the classic diffuse concave ST elevation with PR depression, and contrast with STEMI and benign early repolarization.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG library: pericarditis"}]}, {"id": "acute-risk", "title": "Risk stratification and triage", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Most acute pericarditis is idiopathic or presumed viral and can be managed as an outpatient. The point of risk stratification is to identify who needs admission for monitoring and etiologic workup."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "High-risk features favoring admission (ESC)", "head": ["Category", "Features"], "rows": [["Major", "Fever >38 °C; subacute onset; large effusion (>20 mm echo-free space); cardiac tamponade; failure to respond to NSAID/aspirin after at least 1 week"], ["Minor", "Myopericarditis (troponin elevation); immunosuppression; trauma; oral anticoagulant therapy"]]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Any single major or minor high-risk feature warrants inpatient evaluation. Low-risk patients with none of these can be discharged on empiric therapy with follow-up at about 1 week to check the CRP-guided response. Routine etiologic hunting is <strong>not</strong> recommended in low-risk viral-pattern disease because yield is low; targeted testing is driven by history (TB exposure, malignancy, autoimmune features, recent cardiac procedure)."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "In regions of low tuberculosis prevalence, idiopathic/viral etiology dominates and prognosis is excellent. In high-prevalence settings, TB pericarditis is a leading cause and management diverges sharply (anti-tuberculous therapy, adjunctive steroids in selected cases, high risk of progression to constriction). Geography changes your pretest probability more than any single test."}]}, {"id": "acute-treatment", "title": "Acute pericarditis: NSAID + colchicine dosing", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "First-line therapy is a high-dose NSAID (or aspirin) <strong>plus</strong> colchicine. The COPE and ICAP trials established that adding colchicine roughly halves recurrence and improves remission. Treat until symptom resolution <strong>and</strong> CRP normalization, then taper the NSAID; continue colchicine for the full course."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "First-attack acute pericarditis: drug regimen", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism", "Start / usual dose", "Duration & taper", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Ibuprofen", "Non-selective COX inhibition, anti-inflammatory", "600–800 mg PO q8h", "Until symptoms + CRP resolve (often 1–2 wk), then taper", "Active GI bleed, CKD, decompensated HF, 3rd-trimester pregnancy", "Symptoms, CRP, renal function; add GI protection (PPI)"], ["Aspirin (preferred post-MI / already on ASA)", "COX inhibition", "750–1000 mg PO q8h", "1–2 wk then taper by 250–500 mg every 1–2 wk", "Bleeding, aspirin allergy, children (Reye)", "CRP, GI symptoms; PPI cover"], ["Indomethacin (alternative)", "Potent COX inhibition", "25–50 mg PO q8h", "As above with taper", "Elderly, CAD (reduces coronary flow), GI/renal disease", "CNS side effects, renal, GI"], ["Colchicine", "Inhibits microtubule polymerization; dampens inflammasome/neutrophil activation", "0.5 mg PO BID if ≥70 kg; 0.5 mg PO daily if <70 kg (no loading needed)", "3 months (first attack)", "Severe renal or hepatic impairment; strong CYP3A4 / P-gp inhibitors (clarithromycin, cyclosporine)", "Diarrhea (dose-limiting), CBC (rare myelosuppression), CK/transaminases with statins"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Colchicine is dangerous in renal/hepatic failure and with CYP3A4/P-gp inhibitors.</strong> Co-administration with clarithromycin, azole antifungals, cyclosporine, or use in dialysis patients can precipitate fatal colchicine toxicity (myelosuppression, multi-organ failure). Reduce the dose or avoid. It also potentiates statin myopathy."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Avoid corticosteroids as first-line.</strong> Low-dose prednisone relieves symptoms but is an independent predictor of recurrence and steroid dependence (it favors viral persistence and rebound on taper). Reserve steroids for specific indications: NSAID/colchicine contraindication or failure, systemic autoimmune disease, uremic pericarditis, or pregnancy after the first trimester."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "When corticosteroids are used: low-dose, slow taper", "head": ["Parameter", "Recommendation"], "rows": [["Agent / dose", "Prednisone 0.2–0.5 mg/kg/day (low-to-moderate; avoid ≥1 mg/kg)"], ["Duration", "Maintain until symptom resolution and CRP normalization, then very slow taper"], ["Adjunct", "Always continue colchicine; add calcium/vitamin D and consider bone protection"], ["Taper principle", "Taper one drug at a time, guided by CRP; reduce slowly through the 10–15 mg/day range where relapse clusters"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Practical rule: treat to CRP, not to the calendar.</strong> Continue the NSAID at full dose until the patient is asymptomatic <em>and</em> CRP has normalized, then begin the taper. Premature tapering while CRP is still elevated is a common cause of apparent NSAID failure and early recurrence."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Restrict exercise.</strong> Advise avoidance of strenuous activity until symptom resolution and CRP normalization (and troponin normalization if myopericarditis). Athletes generally restrict for about 3 months from onset per consensus."}]}, {"id": "recurrent", "title": "Recurrent pericarditis and IL-1 blockade", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Recurrence follows roughly 15 to 30% of first attacks and a higher proportion after a first recurrence, especially if steroids were used early or colchicine was omitted. Recurrent pericarditis is defined as a documented first episode, a symptom-free interval of at least 4 to 6 weeks, then recurrence. The therapeutic ladder escalates from optimizing conventional therapy to targeted <strong>IL-1 blockade</strong>."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "Escalation ladder for recurrent pericarditis", "items": ["Confirm the recurrence (symptoms plus objective evidence: CRP rise, new effusion, ECG, or CMR pericardial enhancement).", "Optimize NSAID/aspirin at full anti-inflammatory dose AND extend colchicine to 6 months. Under-dosing and premature taper are the usual reasons for 'refractory' disease.", "If truly colchicine-resistant and corticosteroid-dependent, escalate to an IL-1 blocker (rilonacept or anakinra) rather than climbing the steroid dose.", "Consider adjuncts (azathioprine, IVIG) as steroid-sparing options in selected refractory autoimmune-flavored cases.", "Pericardiectomy is a last resort for truly incessant, treatment-refractory recurrent pericarditis at an experienced center."]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The mechanistic advance is recognizing steroid-dependent, colchicine-resistant recurrent pericarditis as an <strong>IL-1 mediated autoinflammatory</strong> disease. The NLRP3 inflammasome drives IL-1β release; blocking IL-1 signaling produces rapid, durable control. RHAPSODY established rilonacept and AIRTRIP established anakinra in randomized-withdrawal designs."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "IL-1 blockade and steroid-sparing agents for recurrent pericarditis", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism", "Start / dose", "Key contraindication", "Major side effects", "Monitoring / trial"], "rows": [["Rilonacept", "IL-1α and IL-1β 'trap' (fusion protein)", "Load 320 mg SC, then 160 mg SC weekly", "Active/serious infection, active TB", "Injection-site reactions, upper respiratory infection, hyperlipidemia", "Screen TB & hepatitis before start; lipids; RHAPSODY (NEJM, 2021)"], ["Anakinra", "Recombinant IL-1 receptor antagonist (blocks IL-1α and IL-1β)", "100 mg SC daily", "Active infection, neutropenia, untreated latent TB", "Injection-site reactions (very common), neutropenia, infection", "CBC, TB screen; AIRTRIP (JAMA, 2016)"], ["Azathioprine (steroid-sparing)", "Purine antimetabolite, immunosuppressant", "1 mg/kg/day, titrate toward 2–3 mg/kg/day (check TPMT)", "TPMT deficiency, pregnancy, concurrent allopurinol", "Myelosuppression, hepatotoxicity, infection", "TPMT before start; CBC and LFTs serially; slow onset (weeks–months)"], ["IVIG", "Immunomodulation", "400–500 mg/kg/day for ~5 days (regimens vary)", "IgA deficiency with anti-IgA, volume overload", "Aseptic meningitis, thrombosis, renal injury, anaphylaxis", "Renal function, volume status; selected refractory cases"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "In the RHAPSODY randomized-withdrawal trial, rilonacept produced rapid pain resolution and CRP normalization, and randomized withdrawal to placebo led to a far higher recurrence rate than continued rilonacept (hazard ratio for recurrence approximately 0.04). Practically, IL-1 blockers are the preferred escalation over chronic steroids in colchicine-resistant, steroid-dependent disease, and they enable steroid weaning. They are not cures: recurrences can occur after discontinuation, so tapering strategy matters."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Cardiac MRI is the objective adjudicator</strong> when 'recurrence' is uncertain. Late gadolinium enhancement of the pericardium and pericardial edema on T2 confirm active inflammation, distinguish true recurrence from post-pericardiotomy pain or anxiety, and can guide when it is safe to taper anti-inflammatories."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "The RHAPSODY and AIRTRIP trials of IL-1 blockade are worth reading in full.", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/", "label": "PubMed: RHAPSODY / AIRTRIP"}]}, {"id": "effusion", "title": "Pericardial effusion: assessment", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "A pericardial effusion is graded on echo by end-diastolic echo-free space: small (<10 mm), moderate (10 to 20 mm), large (>20 mm). Size does not equal significance. The clinical question is always whether it is hemodynamically compromising (tamponade physiology) and what caused it."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/pericardial-effusion-echo.jpg", "alt": "Parasternal long-axis echo of a large pericardial effusion", "caption": "Parasternal long-axis echo of a large circumferential pericardial effusion (PE): echo-free space anterior to the RV and posterior to the LV/LA.", "credit": "Kalumet — CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Pericardial_effusion.jpg"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Effusion etiologies by fluid character", "head": ["Category", "Examples", "Clues"], "rows": [["Transudative", "Heart failure, cirrhosis, nephrotic syndrome, myxedema", "Often incidental, slowly accumulating, large without tamponade"], ["Exudative / inflammatory", "Viral, idiopathic, autoimmune (SLE, RA), Dressler", "Concurrent pericarditis features, elevated CRP"], ["Malignant", "Lung, breast, lymphoma, melanoma; mesothelioma", "Often large, hemorrhagic, recurrent; cytology and pericardial biopsy"], ["Infectious", "Tuberculous, purulent bacterial, fungal", "TB: high adenosine deaminase, lymphocytic, high constriction risk"], ["Hemopericardium", "Aortic dissection, free-wall rupture post-MI, trauma, procedural", "Rapid, small-volume tamponade; surgical emergency"], ["Metabolic", "Uremia, hypothyroidism", "Uremic: dialysis-responsive; myxedema: may be very large"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Diagnostic pericardiocentesis fluid analysis mirrors pleural fluid logic: send cell count, protein, LDH, glucose, cytology, Gram stain and culture, and in the right setting adenosine deaminase (ADA) and mycobacterial studies for TB. Light-criteria transudate-versus-exudate discrimination is imperfect for pericardial fluid; cytology and ADA carry more decision weight. Grossly bloody fluid is not automatically hemopericardium (malignancy and TB bleed too)."}]}, {"id": "tamponade-patho", "title": "Cardiac tamponade: pathophysiology and bedside signs", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Tamponade is decompensated pericardial pressure: fluid raises intrapericardial pressure until it equals and then exceeds chamber diastolic pressures, collapsing filling. Cardiac output falls, compensatory tachycardia and vasoconstriction rise, and untreated it progresses to pulseless electrical activity. It is a <strong>clinical and hemodynamic</strong> diagnosis; echo supports but does not replace the bedside assessment."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Beck triad", "def": "Hypotension, muffled heart sounds, and jugular venous distension. Classic but insensitive; more typical of acute surgical tamponade."}, {"term": "Pulsus paradoxus", "def": "Exaggerated inspiratory fall in systolic BP >10 mmHg. Reflects ventricular interdependence: inspiratory RV filling shifts the septum and impairs LV stroke volume. Measured by cuff, noting the range over which Korotkoff sounds are heard only in expiration."}, {"term": "Equalization of diastolic pressures", "def": "Intrapericardial pressure equalizes RA, RV, PA diastolic, and PCWP end-diastolic pressures (all elevated, within roughly 5 mmHg)."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Pulsus paradoxus can be absent</strong> in tamponade with coexisting elevated LV diastolic pressure (severe LVH, aortic regurgitation), atrial septal defect, or positive-pressure ventilation. Its absence does not exclude tamponade. Conversely it appears in severe asthma/COPD, massive PE, and RV infarction, so it is supportive, not specific."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The JVP in tamponade shows a preserved <strong>x descent</strong> with a <strong>blunted or absent y descent</strong>, because the constrained heart cannot fill in early diastole. This is a key contrast to constriction, where the y descent is prominent (rapid early filling that then abruptly halts). The Kussmaul sign (inspiratory rise in JVP) is characteristic of constriction and RV infarction, <strong>not</strong> classic tamponade."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic for the JVP waveforms: tamponade = 'ta-<em>x</em>' (x preserved, y blunted); constriction = 'con-<em>y</em>' (prominent y, the W/M pattern).</strong> Tamponade abolishes early diastolic filling (no y); constriction allows a rapid early y descent that stops abruptly against the rigid shell."}]}, {"id": "tamponade-echo", "title": "Tamponade: echocardiographic findings", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Echo confirms the effusion and demonstrates the hemodynamic consequence. The chamber that collapses reflects the pressure hierarchy: the lowest-pressure chambers give way first."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Echo signs of tamponade (in order of appearance/sensitivity)", "head": ["Sign", "What it means", "Notes"], "rows": [["RA collapse (late diastole/systole)", "Intrapericardial pressure exceeds RA pressure", "Sensitive; more specific if it lasts more than one-third of the cardiac cycle"], ["RV free-wall diastolic collapse", "Intrapericardial pressure exceeds low RV diastolic pressure", "More specific; may be masked by RV hypertrophy or elevated RV pressures"], ["Respirophasic transvalvular flow variation", "Exaggerated interdependence", "Tricuspid inflow increases and mitral inflow decreases on inspiration; mitral E variation >25%, tricuspid >40–60% supports tamponade"], ["Plethoric IVC with <50% inspiratory collapse", "Elevated, fixed RA pressure", "Sensitive; a small, collapsing IVC argues strongly against tamponade"], ["Systolic septal shift / 'swinging heart'", "Total cardiac volume fixed; septum shifts with respiration", "The swinging heart underlies electrical alternans on ECG"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Regional or low-pressure tamponade breaks the classic rules. After cardiac surgery a loculated clot can compress a single chamber (often the LA or RV) without a large circumferential effusion, and transthoracic windows may miss it, so TEE is the study of choice. In the hypovolemic patient (dialysis, hemorrhage) tamponade can occur at low intrapericardial pressure ('low-pressure tamponade') with subtle collapse; volume loading transiently unmasks it. RV collapse can be absent when RV pressures are high (pulmonary hypertension), so a normal-appearing RV does not exclude tamponade in that population."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "On ECG, low voltage and <strong>electrical alternans</strong> (beat-to-beat QRS amplitude variation from the swinging heart) are supportive of a large effusion with tamponade physiology, though neither is sensitive. Sinus tachycardia is nearly universal; its absence in a sick patient suggests uremia, hypothyroidism, or beta-blockade."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Electrical alternans and low voltage in a large pericardial effusion are pattern-recognition ECG findings.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG library: electrical alternans"}]}, {"id": "tamponade-management", "title": "Tamponade and pericardiocentesis: management", "body": [{"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "Management of hemodynamically significant tamponade", "items": ["Recognize clinically: hypotension, tachycardia, elevated JVP, pulsus paradoxus, effusion on echo. Do not delay for a perfect study in a crashing patient.", "Temporize with IV volume (cautiously) to support RV filling while arranging drainage; avoid positive-pressure ventilation if possible, which further impairs venous return.", "Definitive therapy is drainage. Echo-guided pericardiocentesis is first-line for most medical effusions; surgical drainage (subxiphoid window or thoracotomy) is preferred for hemopericardium from dissection/rupture, purulent effusion, or loculated post-surgical collections.", "Send fluid for cell count, cytology, culture/Gram stain, ADA/TB studies as indicated.", "Leave a pericardial drain for large or malignant effusions to reduce early re-accumulation; monitor for recurrence."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Do not perform needle pericardiocentesis in suspected aortic dissection with hemopericardium.</strong> Decompression can accelerate bleeding and hemodynamic collapse; the patient needs emergent surgery. Similarly, free-wall rupture after MI is a surgical problem. Pericardiocentesis in these settings is a temporizing bridge at most, only if in extremis."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Avoid aggressive positive-pressure ventilation and vasodilators.</strong> In preload-dependent tamponade physiology, intubation and PEEP can precipitate arrest by dropping venous return. Where feasible, drain the pericardium before or in parallel with securing the airway, and keep the patient full."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Rarely, drainage precipitates <strong>pericardial decompression syndrome</strong>: paradoxical hemodynamic deterioration, pulmonary edema, or even transient LV/RV dysfunction after fluid removal, thought to relate to abrupt changes in loading and coronary perfusion. Remove fluid in a controlled, staged fashion for very large chronic effusions and monitor closely afterward."}]}, {"id": "constriction-patho", "title": "Constrictive pericarditis: pathophysiology", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Constriction is a fibrotic, sometimes calcified, non-compliant pericardium encasing the heart. Early diastolic filling is rapid and unimpeded until the ventricle abruptly hits the rigid shell, at which point filling stops. The two defining physiologic consequences are <strong>exaggerated ventricular interdependence</strong> and <strong>dissociation of intrathoracic from intracardiac pressures</strong>."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/pericardial-calcification-cxr.png", "alt": "Lateral chest radiograph showing pericardial calcification", "caption": "Lateral chest radiograph: a rim of pericardial calcification along the cardiac border — a classic (though not universal) clue to constrictive pericarditis.", "credit": "Hellerhoff — CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:33-02-Pericarditis_calcarea_seitlich.png"}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "In the normal heart, inspiration lowers intrathoracic pressure, which is transmitted to the pulmonary veins and the left heart, so the LA-to-LV filling gradient is roughly preserved. In constriction the rigid pericardium <strong>shields</strong> the cardiac chambers from the inspiratory drop, so pulmonary venous (thoracic) pressure falls but LV diastolic pressure does not, the LA-to-LV gradient falls, and left-heart filling decreases on inspiration. That displaced volume goes to the right heart, bowing the septum leftward. On expiration the reverse occurs. This respiratory ping-pong across a fixed total volume is the engine behind every constrictive sign."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Kussmaul sign", "def": "Failure of JVP to fall (or a rise) with inspiration. The rigid pericardium prevents the inspiratory augmentation of RV filling from being accommodated, so systemic venous pressure stays elevated. Seen in constriction and RV infarction; not classic tamponade."}, {"term": "Pericardial knock", "def": "Early diastolic high-pitched sound from the abrupt halt of ventricular filling against the rigid pericardium. Corresponds to the y descent and the dip of the square-root sign."}, {"term": "Effusive-constrictive pericarditis", "def": "Coexisting effusion (tamponade physiology) plus visceral pericardial constriction. After pericardiocentesis, RA pressure fails to fall by at least 50% or to below 10 mmHg, revealing the underlying constriction."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Common causes of constrictive pericarditis", "head": ["Category", "Examples"], "rows": [["Idiopathic / viral", "Most common in developed countries; often post-viral"], ["Post-cardiac surgery / post-radiation", "CABG, valve surgery; mediastinal radiation (breast, lymphoma) — often years later, may coexist with myocardial and valve disease"], ["Infectious", "Tuberculous (dominant cause worldwide), purulent bacterial"], ["Connective tissue / inflammatory", "RA, SLE, post-pericardiotomy syndrome"], ["Other", "Uremia, malignancy, asbestos, sarcoid"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Transient constriction</strong> is real and treatable. A subset of patients with an inflammatory pericardial process develop reversible constrictive physiology that resolves over 2 to 3 months with anti-inflammatory therapy. If the patient is clinically stable and the pericardium shows active inflammation (CRP up, CMR enhancement), a trial of NSAID/colchicine/steroid before committing to pericardiectomy is appropriate."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Pericardial calcification on chest radiograph and CT is a classic (though not universal) sign of chronic constriction.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: pericardial calcification"}]}, {"id": "constriction-echo", "title": "Constriction: echocardiographic findings", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The Mayo Clinic echocardiographic criteria (Welch et al., 2014) brought discipline to the echo diagnosis of constriction. The three most useful signs are respiration-related septal shift (septal bounce), preserved or increased medial mitral annular e' (<em>annulus paradoxus/reversus</em>), and hepatic vein expiratory diastolic flow reversal. Respirophasic mitral inflow variation adds specificity."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Echo signs of constrictive pericarditis", "head": ["Sign", "Finding", "Physiologic basis"], "rows": [["Septal bounce / shudder", "Early-diastolic leftward septal shift with inspiration, rightward with expiration", "Beat-to-beat interdependence within a fixed pericardial volume"], ["Respirophasic mitral inflow variation", "Mitral E velocity falls >25% on the first inspiratory beat (tricuspid E rises, often >40%)", "Dissociation of thoracic and cardiac pressures reduces the LA–LV gradient on inspiration"], ["Annulus paradoxus", "E/e' does NOT rise (or falls) despite high filling pressures; e' is preserved/increased", "Tethered lateral wall shifts longitudinal relaxation medially; the usual E/e'–filling-pressure relationship inverts"], ["Annulus reversus", "Medial (septal) e' ≥ lateral e' (normally lateral > medial)", "Lateral annulus is tethered by pericardium; medial motion is relatively spared or augmented"], ["Hepatic vein expiratory diastolic flow reversal", "Prominent diastolic flow reversal in expiration", "Expiratory augmentation of RV filling is limited by the rigid shell, backing flow into the hepatic veins"], ["IVC plethora", "Dilated IVC with reduced inspiratory collapse", "Elevated, fixed systemic venous pressure"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Annulus reversus is among the most useful discriminators from restrictive cardiomyopathy.</strong> In restriction the myocardium itself is diseased, so tissue-Doppler e' velocities are globally <em>reduced</em> (typically below 8 cm/s) and lateral remains greater than medial. In constriction the myocardium is intrinsically normal but the lateral wall is tethered by the pericardium, so medial e' is preserved or high and may exceed lateral e'. Reading the mitral annular tissue-Doppler is often the fastest way to separate the two at the bedside echo machine."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic: constriction spares the muscle, restriction destroys it.</strong> So constriction keeps e' <em>high</em> (annulus reversus, E/e' paradoxically low) while restriction drops e' <em>low</em> with a high E/e'. Combine with the respiration signs (septal bounce, >25% mitral variation, hepatic vein reversal) and the diagnosis usually declares itself on echo before you go to cath."}]}, {"id": "constriction-cath", "title": "Constriction: right and left heart catheterization", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "When echo is equivocal, simultaneous right and left heart catheterization with respiratory recording is the reference standard. The diagnosis rests on three linked findings: equalization of end-diastolic pressures, the dip-and-plateau (square-root sign), and enhanced ventricular interdependence (RV-LV systolic discordance)."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Invasive hemodynamics of constriction", "head": ["Finding", "Definition", "Interpretation"], "rows": [["Equalization of diastolic pressures", "RA, RV end-diastolic, PA diastolic, and PCWP within about 5 mmHg of each other, all elevated", "Rigid shell transmits a common constraining pressure to all chambers"], ["Square-root / dip-and-plateau sign", "Steep early-diastolic dip then abrupt plateau in the RV (and LV) pressure trace", "Rapid unimpeded early filling that halts abruptly against the pericardium"], ["Prominent y descent (RA)", "Deep y with preserved x, giving an M/W-shaped waveform", "Rapid early diastolic filling; contrast with the blunted y of tamponade"], ["Kussmaul sign (invasive)", "RA pressure fails to fall / rises with inspiration", "Inspiratory venous return not accommodated by the rigid pericardium"], ["Ventricular interdependence (discordance)", "RV systolic pressure rises while LV systolic pressure falls during inspiration (systolic area index >1.1)", "The most specific sign; dynamic respiratory competition for a fixed volume"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The <strong>systolic area index</strong> (Hurrell/Talreja) formalizes interdependence: it is the ratio of the RV systolic pressure–time area to the LV systolic pressure–time area in inspiration versus expiration. A value <strong>>1.1</strong> discriminates constriction from restriction with high sensitivity and specificity, outperforming static equalization criteria (which restriction can mimic). This is the modern invasive answer to the classic 'they both have equalized pressures' problem: look at the <em>dynamic, respiration-linked discordance</em>, not just the resting numbers."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Why static criteria fail: constriction vs restriction at cath", "head": ["Feature", "Constriction", "Restriction"], "rows": [["RV/LV systolic pressures with respiration", "Discordant (RV up, LV down on inspiration)", "Concordant (both fall on inspiration)"], ["LVEDP vs RVEDP", "Equal (within about 5 mmHg)", "LVEDP typically exceeds RVEDP by >5 mmHg"], ["RV systolic pressure", "Usually <50 mmHg", "Often >50 mmHg (pulmonary hypertension)"], ["RVEDP / RV systolic ratio", ">1/3", "<1/3"], ["Square-root sign", "Present", "May be present (less specific)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Constriction and restriction can <strong>coexist</strong> (classically after mediastinal radiation, which scars both pericardium and myocardium and injures valves and coronaries). In these mixed cases neither echo nor cath gives a clean answer, and pericardiectomy has higher risk and lower benefit. CMR and CT to assess pericardial thickness, calcification, and myocardial involvement, plus multidisciplinary review, guide the decision."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "Review the square-root sign, RA W/M waveform, and RV-LV systolic discordance tracings.", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/", "label": "PMC: constrictive hemodynamics review"}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "label": "Labeled RHC pressure tracings — constriction vs restriction (open-access, CC BY)", "text": "Dean & Kern: the RV dip-and-plateau / square-root waveform and the discordant respirophasic LV–RV pressures that separate constrictive pericarditis from restrictive cardiomyopathy", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11308782/"}]}, {"id": "three-way", "title": "The comparison table: constriction vs restriction vs tamponade", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "These three entities all present with elevated filling pressures and dyspnea, and confusing them changes management drastically (pericardiectomy versus transplant/medical versus emergent drainage). This master table consolidates the discriminators from the preceding sections."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Master comparison", "head": ["Feature", "Constrictive pericarditis", "Restrictive cardiomyopathy", "Cardiac tamponade"], "rows": [["Core lesion", "Rigid/scarred pericardium; normal myocardium", "Stiff, infiltrated myocardium; normal pericardium", "Fluid under pressure in the pericardial space"], ["JVP y descent", "Prominent (rapid early filling, W/M pattern)", "Prominent", "Blunted/absent (no early filling)"], ["Kussmaul sign", "Present", "Often present", "Usually absent"], ["Pulsus paradoxus", "Usually absent", "Absent", "Present (hallmark)"], ["Septal bounce (echo)", "Present", "Absent", "Absent (swinging heart instead)"], ["Respirophasic mitral E variation", ">25%", "<10% (minimal)", ">25% (with tricuspid variation)"], ["Tissue Doppler e'", "Preserved/high; annulus reversus (medial ≥ lateral)", "Reduced (<8 cm/s); lateral > medial", "Variable (limited by tamponade physiology)"], ["E/e'", "Low/normal (annulus paradoxus)", "High (>15)", "Not the primary discriminator"], ["Hepatic vein flow reversal", "Expiratory diastolic reversal", "Inspiratory diastolic reversal", "Not the primary discriminator"], ["RV vs LV systolic pressure (respiration)", "Discordant; systolic area index >1.1", "Concordant", "Both fall together"], ["LVEDP vs RVEDP", "Equalized (within ~5 mmHg)", "LVEDP > RVEDP by >5 mmHg", "Equalized diastolic pressures"], ["BNP", "Relatively low/normal", "Markedly elevated", "Variable"], ["Pericardial thickness (CT/CMR)", "Often thickened/calcified (can be normal)", "Normal", "Effusion present"], ["Definitive therapy", "Pericardiectomy (or anti-inflammatory if transient)", "Treat the underlying disease (amyloid, etc.); transplant", "Pericardiocentesis / surgical drainage"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>BNP is an underused tiebreaker.</strong> Restrictive cardiomyopathy (a diseased, stretched myocardium) drives BNP high, whereas constriction (a normal myocardium in a rigid box) keeps BNP relatively low. A markedly elevated BNP in a patient with equalized pressures should make you doubt pure constriction and look hard for infiltrative disease such as amyloid."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "When infiltrative restriction is on the table, chase the etiology aggressively: cardiac amyloidosis (technetium-pyrophosphate scintigraphy for ATTR, serum/urine free light chains and biopsy for AL), sarcoidosis, hemochromatosis, and hypereosinophilic/endomyocardial fibrosis. The distinction is not academic: transthyretin amyloid now has disease-modifying therapy, and misdiagnosing amyloid as operable constriction sends a patient to a high-risk pericardiectomy that will not help."}]}, {"id": "pericardiectomy", "title": "Definitive management of constriction and special etiologies", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "For established chronic constriction with symptoms, <strong>radical pericardiectomy</strong> at an experienced center is the definitive treatment. Medical therapy (diuretics for congestion) is palliative and does not reverse the mechanical constraint. Timing matters: operating before advanced cachexia, hepatic congestion, and low-output state improves outcomes, but perioperative mortality remains meaningful and is highest in radiation-induced and mixed constriction-restriction."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Decision pathway in suspected constriction", "items": ["Confirm constrictive physiology with echo (septal bounce, >25% mitral variation, annulus reversus, hepatic vein reversal) and, if equivocal, invasive hemodynamics (equalization, square-root sign, systolic area index >1.1).", "Characterize the pericardium with CT (calcification, thickness) and CMR (thickness, inflammation via late gadolinium enhancement).", "If active inflammation is present and the patient is stable, trial anti-inflammatory therapy for 2–3 months to capture reversible/transient constriction.", "If chronic, calcified, non-inflamed constriction with symptoms, refer for pericardiectomy — earlier rather than after end-organ decline.", "Exclude coexisting restriction (radiation, amyloid) before surgery, since mixed disease predicts poor surgical benefit."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Etiology-specific management points", "head": ["Etiology", "Distinguishing management"], "rows": [["Tuberculous pericarditis", "Anti-tuberculous therapy; adjunctive corticosteroids in selected patients; high progression to constriction — monitor closely"], ["Uremic pericarditis", "Intensify/initiate dialysis (usually responds); NSAIDs less effective; avoid heavy anticoagulation (hemorrhagic risk)"], ["Post-MI: early (peri-infarction) vs Dressler", "Early pericarditis days after MI — favor aspirin and avoid high-dose NSAIDs/steroids (impair healing); Dressler is a later immune-mediated syndrome, now rare with reperfusion"], ["Post-pericardiotomy syndrome", "Immune-mediated after cardiac surgery; NSAID + colchicine; colchicine also reduces incidence prophylactically (COPPS)"], ["Malignant effusion", "Drainage with catheter, treat the underlying malignancy; consider pericardial window for recurrence; poor overall prognosis"], ["Radiation-associated", "Often mixed constriction-restriction with valve/coronary/myocardial injury; surgical results poorer; multidisciplinary evaluation"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>After acute MI, avoid high-dose NSAIDs and corticosteroids for peri-infarction pericarditis.</strong> They impair myocardial scar formation and raise the risk of wall thinning and rupture. Aspirin is the preferred anti-inflammatory in this setting, and colchicine is a reasonable adjunct."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The COPPS and COPPS-2 trials showed perioperative colchicine reduces post-pericardiotomy syndrome, and COPPS-2 also reduced postoperative atrial fibrillation after cardiac surgery, though at the cost of GI intolerance. This is the same anti-inflammatory drug reappearing across the entire pericardial-disease spectrum — first attack, recurrence prevention, and surgical prophylaxis — which is why colchicine is worth mastering thoroughly."}]}, {"id": "pitfalls", "title": "High-yield pitfalls and board traps", "body": [{"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "Traps that catch residents and fellows", "items": ["Calling diffuse ST elevation 'pericarditis' without checking for PR depression, reciprocal changes, and the clinical story — missing a wraparound-LAD STEMI.", "Starting steroids first-line for a first attack and generating a steroid-dependent recurrent course.", "Tapering the NSAID while CRP is still elevated, then blaming 'NSAID failure' for the relapse.", "Assuming absent pulsus paradoxus rules out tamponade (it can be absent with elevated LVEDP, ASD, or on positive-pressure ventilation).", "Needle-decompressing a hemopericardium from aortic dissection instead of rushing to surgery.", "Diagnosing 'constriction' on equalized diastolic pressures alone and missing restriction — always test the respiratory discordance (systolic area index).", "Forgetting that a normal pericardial thickness does NOT exclude constriction (a substantial minority have normal thickness); physiology beats anatomy.", "Sending a radiation or amyloid patient to pericardiectomy for what is really restriction (or mixed disease)."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>One-line frameworks:</strong> tamponade = 'x preserved, y gone, pulsus present'; constriction = 'prominent y, Kussmaul, annulus reversus, systolic discordance'; restriction = 'low e', high E/e', high BNP, concordant pressures.'"}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "When the whole picture will not resolve — dyspnea, elevated JVP, equivocal echo — the highest-yield next test depends on the question. For constriction-versus-restriction, go to invasive simultaneous RV-LV hemodynamics with respiration and to CMR/CT. For occult tamponade after surgery, go to TEE. For infiltrative disease, go to PYP scintigraphy, light chains, and biopsy. Match the test to the specific physiologic question rather than reflexively repeating the transthoracic echo."}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 34-year-old man presents with 3 days of sharp chest pain that worsens when lying flat and improves when he sits forward. Temperature is 37.2 °C. ECG shows diffuse concave ST-segment elevation with PR-segment depression and reciprocal PR elevation in aVR. Troponin is normal. Echocardiography shows a trivial pericardial effusion without tamponade physiology. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial therapy?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Prednisone 1 mg/kg/day with a slow taper"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Ibuprofen 600–800 mg every 8 hours plus colchicine 0.5 mg twice daily"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Colchicine 0.5 mg twice daily alone"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Anakinra 100 mg subcutaneously daily"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Urgent pericardiocentesis"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is a low-risk first episode of acute pericarditis (2 of 4 criteria met: positional pleuritic pain and typical ECG). First-line therapy is a high-dose NSAID PLUS colchicine, a combination shown in COPE and ICAP to roughly halve recurrence. Corticosteroids (A) are avoided early because they promote steroid-dependent recurrence, and are reserved for NSAID/colchicine failure or specific indications. Colchicine alone (C) is inadequate for the acute attack. IL-1 blockade (D) is for colchicine-resistant, steroid-dependent recurrent disease. There is no tamponade, so pericardiocentesis (E) is not indicated."}, {"stem": "A 61-year-old woman with prior mediastinal radiation for Hodgkin lymphoma presents with progressive edema and ascites. JVP is elevated and rises with inspiration. Echo shows a septal bounce, respirophasic mitral inflow variation of 30%, and a medial mitral annular e' of 12 cm/s that exceeds the lateral e' of 8 cm/s. Which finding best supports constrictive pericarditis over restrictive cardiomyopathy?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Elevated jugular venous pressure"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Presence of a pericardial effusion"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Medial (septal) e' greater than lateral e' (annulus reversus)"}, {"key": "D", "text": "A markedly elevated BNP"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Reduced left ventricular ejection fraction"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "Annulus reversus (medial e' at least equal to lateral e') is a strong discriminator for constriction. In constriction the myocardium is intrinsically normal but the lateral wall is tethered by pericardium, so medial e' is preserved or increased and exceeds lateral e', with e' velocities remaining high. In restriction the myocardium is diseased and e' is globally reduced with lateral greater than medial. Elevated JVP (A) occurs in both. BNP (D) is typically higher in restriction. Reduced EF (E) is not characteristic of either early. This patient's radiation history raises the possibility of mixed constriction-restriction, which lowers surgical benefit."}, {"stem": "A 72-year-old man on hemodialysis becomes hypotensive with a blood pressure of 84/60 mmHg and heart rate of 118/min. JVP is elevated with a preserved x descent and a blunted y descent. Systolic pressure falls 18 mmHg during inspiration. Echo shows a moderate circumferential effusion with right atrial systolic collapse, right ventricular diastolic collapse, and a plethoric IVC. Which additional finding is most consistent with the diagnosis?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Prominent y descent in the jugular venous pulse"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Inspiratory increase in mitral inflow velocity"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Increased tricuspid inflow and decreased mitral inflow during inspiration"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Kussmaul sign"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Pericardial knock on auscultation"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "This is cardiac tamponade (hypotension, tachycardia, elevated JVP with blunted y descent, pulsus paradoxus, chamber collapse, plethoric IVC). Enhanced ventricular interdependence produces respirophasic transvalvular flow: inspiration increases right-heart (tricuspid) inflow and decreases left-heart (mitral) inflow. A prominent y descent (A) and pericardial knock (E) are features of constriction, not tamponade (tamponade abolishes early diastolic filling, blunting the y). Inspiratory increase in mitral inflow (B) is the opposite of tamponade physiology. Kussmaul sign (D) is characteristic of constriction and RV infarction, not classic tamponade."}, {"stem": "A 45-year-old woman has had three episodes of pericarditis over 8 months. Each recurred within weeks of tapering prednisone, and she remains dependent on 12.5 mg/day despite colchicine. CRP is elevated and cardiac MRI shows pericardial late gadolinium enhancement. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Increase prednisone to 1 mg/kg/day indefinitely"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Discontinue colchicine and observe"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Initiate rilonacept (IL-1 blockade)"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Proceed directly to pericardiectomy"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Start warfarin to prevent constriction"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "This is colchicine-resistant, corticosteroid-dependent recurrent pericarditis with objective active inflammation (elevated CRP, CMR enhancement) — an IL-1 mediated autoinflammatory phenotype. IL-1 blockade with rilonacept (RHAPSODY trial) or anakinra (AIRTRIP) produces rapid, durable remission and enables steroid weaning, and is preferred over escalating steroids (A), which worsen dependence and toxicity. Stopping colchicine (B) would remove a beneficial agent. Pericardiectomy (D) is a last resort for truly incessant refractory disease. Anticoagulation (E) has no role in preventing constriction and is potentially harmful."}, {"stem": "During simultaneous right and left heart catheterization for unexplained heart failure, RA, RV end-diastolic, PA diastolic, and pulmonary capillary wedge pressures are all elevated and within 4 mmHg of each other. During inspiration, RV systolic pressure rises while LV systolic pressure falls, yielding a systolic area index of 1.3. Which statement is most accurate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "These findings are diagnostic of restrictive cardiomyopathy"}, {"key": "B", "text": "The discordant respiratory change in RV and LV systolic pressures supports constriction"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Equalization of diastolic pressures alone reliably distinguishes constriction from restriction"}, {"key": "D", "text": "A systolic area index >1.1 favors restriction over constriction"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Pericardial thickness on imaging must be increased to diagnose constriction"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Enhanced ventricular interdependence — RV systolic pressure rising as LV systolic pressure falls during inspiration (discordance), quantified by a systolic area index >1.1 — is the most specific invasive finding for constriction and reliably separates it from restriction, where the two ventricles change concordantly. Restriction (A) shows concordant systolic pressures and often LVEDP > RVEDP. Equalization of diastolic pressures alone (C) can occur in both and is not discriminating. A systolic area index >1.1 favors constriction, not restriction (D). A meaningful minority of constriction cases have normal pericardial thickness, so normal thickness does not exclude it (E) — physiology beats anatomy."}], "references": ["2015 ESC Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pericardial Diseases (European Heart Journal)", "Imazio M et al. COPE trial: Colchicine for acute pericarditis (Circulation)", "Imazio M et al. ICAP trial: Colchicine in acute pericarditis (New England Journal of Medicine)", "Klein AL et al. RHAPSODY trial: Rilonacept for recurrent pericarditis (New England Journal of Medicine, 2021)", "Brucato A et al. AIRTRIP trial: Anakinra for recurrent pericarditis (JAMA, 2016)", "Welch TD et al. Mayo Clinic echocardiographic criteria for constrictive pericarditis (Circulation: Cardiovascular Imaging, 2014)", "Talreja DR, Nishimura RA et al. Constrictive pericarditis in the modern era: novel criteria for diagnosis in the cardiac catheterization laboratory, including the systolic area index (Journal of the American College of Cardiology)", "Imazio M et al. COPPS and COPPS-2 trials: Colchicine for the prevention of postpericardiotomy syndrome (JAMA)"]};
